post_text: Due to the COVID-19 emergency, the South Carolina State Department of Education has approved for Spartanburg District Four students to receive free lunch and free breakfast estimated to last through December beginning immediately. All students in the community who are 18 years or younger will qualify. Students who are enrolled in daily attendance will receive meals in person at school, and to-go meals for days when not in attendance will be available for pick-up upon dismissal beginning Monday, September 14th. For questions or those interested in receiving free meals for children who are not attending school, please contact Ms. Audra Terry at Spartanburg Four. You can email her at aterry@spartanburg4.org or call at 864-476-3186.

post_text:
It’s time for the Wolverines to take the field and play football! District Four will follow guidelines by the South Carolina High School League for social distancing and have limited seating to accommodate the families of football players, cheerleaders, and band members. No one will be admitted to the game without a pre-sold ticket. Passes will not be accepted for entry. Masks are required for all those entering the stadium.

In an effort to accommodate the District Four community who will not be allowed to enter due to social distancing, we will attempt to livestream the games for free to the general public. We will post links when they become available.
Spartanburg District Four continues to try to make sure our students, staff, and families stay safe through this process.

We appreciate your understanding in our following SCHSL rules in order for our football players, cheerleaders, and band members to have the opportunity to participate this season.

In following the South Carolina High School League requirements for seating, all home volleyball games will be played at Woodruff High School.

District Four will prioritize the limited seating to accommodate the families of our athletes and those of opposing teams. No one will be admitted without a pre-sold ticket. Passes will not be accepted for entry. Masks are also required for all those who enter.

Spartanburg District Four continues to try to make sure our students, staff, and families stay safe through this process.

We appreciate your understanding in our following SCHSL rules in order for our athletes to get to participate this season.

post_text:
UPDATE:

Spartanburg District Four would like to thank the parents, students, and staff for a smooth opening for the 2020-2021 school year.

As promised, the district will continue to do what is best for our students. It has been decided for the weeks of September 7th-September 25th, the district will continue to run a hybrid model with students reporting on A Days and B Days.

We are encouraged by our ability to keep our students socially distanced and by the low number of positive cases in our schools. Our hope is to slowly transition students back into our buildings making sure our students, teachers, and staff are safe and healthy in the process.

Again, we thank you for being flexible, and we appreciate your help in this unprecedented time.

post_text: Congratulations to WHS Senior Joanna Jones, who tied for 1st Place in the 11th grade in the Law Day Essay Contest sponsored by the Spartanburg Bar Association. Joanna received her award this summer from Judge Hayes at the Spartanburg County Courthouse. Her essay was a historical review and argument about the present status of women's suffrage in the United States. Teachers Mrs. Lawson and Dr. Gagliardi were her sponsors and advised Joanna from historical and language arts perspectives.

post_text:
UPDATE:
Spartanburg Four has received guidance from the Department of Education regarding face covering guidelines.

As previously stated in our Return to School Plan, face coverings are mandated while boarding, riding, and exiting school buses.

Additionally, students and staff must wear a face covering when entering a school building, moving through the hallways, during carline/drop off or pickup, and when social distancing is not possible or optimal.

Spartanburg Four is starting the school year using a hybrid model and in most cases, students will not be required to wear a face covering inside a classroom or during special activities outside the classroom while under the hybrid model. Based on the activity and proximity of the students, the teacher will determine when a mask is needed.

Special considerations will be made for those students who are younger than two years old, who have trouble breathing, who are unable to remove the covering without assistance, and those with special healthcare or educational needs (IEP, 504, IHP).

State Superintendent Molly Spearman issued a mandate Friday requiring masks to be worn in all schools beginning August 3. Spartanburg District 4 is waiting for guidance from the state department outlining some specific details of the mask requirement. We will share that information with our community on Monday.

To give parents additional time to consider the district’s virtual education program, the window for virtual registration will be extended through Wednesday, Aug 5, 2020, at 12 noon. If you wish to move your student to the virtual platform, please contact your child’s school principal to set up a virtual meeting and complete a Declaration of Intent form.

We appreciate your support and understanding during this time of seemingly constant change!

ON LINE REGISTRATION is available!

The online enrollment platform to complete registration forms is now OPEN.

Parents must have a parent portal login to complete forms. Parents who do not have parent portal may download the parent portal application from the school’s website. The parent portal application can be dropped off at your student’s school.

Directions to complete online enrollment can be found on each school’s website, district website, as well here: spartanburg4.org.

The online registration portal will close on Friday, July 31 at 5 pm.

NEW STUDENTS to the district may also begin enrollment using the following link: spartanburg4.org

shared_text:
Ashley Bennett
July 16 at 5:16 PM ·

Dear SC Teacher,
Before you scroll because the last thing you want to read about is more politics, I ask you to give me just a second of your time. I promise this is not political. What I propose is that you make a decision? Not a political decision. Not even a candidate decision, but a right-now-in-this-moment decision to have the best school year ever in 2020-2021. Make a decision, no matter the situation or circumstances, that you will speak life into your students, and your classroom will be one of positivity whether in person or virtually. Make a decision that when people speak negatively of you, your profession, or even of your students that their opinions (and that is truly all they are) don’t have a place in your mind, heart, or classroom. We are teachers. We do the impossible each and everyday, and we can decide to do education in 2020 better than ever.
Love,
A fellow teacher whose identity, worth, and joy are found in her Lord and Savior, Jesus Christ and not in what others say or circumstances.

Spartanburg County School Districts Release Joint Response to Reopening Plans

Spartanburg County, S.C. - In light of Governor McMaster’s press conference earlier today, all Spartanburg County superintendents are working diligently together to evaluate each district’s plan to determine the appropriate next steps.

Given today’s new guidance from Governor McMaster, modifications to districts’ reopening plans may be necessary. Each district will communicate any changes to their previous reopening plans as quickly as possible. Spartanburg County superintendents wish to extend their appreciation for the continued support and patience from parents, teachers, students, and community partners.

Each Spartanburg County school district is committed to providing the safest and best learning experience possible for all students during this uncertain time.

ATHLETICS UPDATE for 9th-12th STUDENTS:

Summer Workouts will begin Monday, June 8 for high school athletes who are playing a fall sport.

Several guidelines have been released by the state that we must follow.

Each athlete who is going to participate in a weight workout or a practice this summer must register with the WHS Athletic Department.

Registration will be held in the WHS Lobby this Wednesday-Friday, June 3-5, from 8am- 4pm.

There is also an optional Parent Meeting on Thursday, June 4, at 7 pm in the stadium for anyone who wants additional information. Parents will also be able to register athletes after the Parent Meeting on Thursday. In the event of inclement weather, the Parent Meeting will be moved into the WHS gym.

A current 2019-2020 physical or a new physical dated after April 1, 2020 must be on file to participate. After July 1, all athletes must have a physical dated after April 1, 2020 to continue to workout or practice.

post_text:
WPS announces the Donna Cannon Award recipient - Giuliana Parris!

Giuliana received a plaque to take home, and her name will be added to the school plaque which is displayed in the office.

The Donna Cannon Award is given in memory of a former teacher of Woodruff Primary School who passed away at a young age. Her husband, Mr. John Cannon, former principal of Woodruff Elementary School, and their daughters, Jennifer and Emily, provide this award each year for an outstanding 2nd grade student.

It's Teacher Appreciation Week and District Four has some AMAZING educators. Our teachers have gone above and beyond to help students and parents during this time. In honor of the wonderful things going on in our district, we would like to share just how special the teachers are to you!

You can share your stories by emailing spartanburgdistrict4info@gmail.com and we will do our best to get your story on Facebook. You don't have to have pictures, we can just post your story!

Our first shoutout goes to Mrs. Kuronya! She drove over forty miles to meet with one of her students to help with AP Biology. Her mother stated, "This sweet lady drove all the way to our house to help my stressed out child."

Thanks Mrs. K for going above and beyond for your students!

post_text:
The Spartanburg School District Superintendents have joined with the Spartanburg Academic Movement to gather information about county-wide “wins” and “challenges” during this unique time.

SAM would like to highlight some of the wonderful experiences parents, students, and teachers have had, and they would also be interested in knowing the challenges during this learning period away from school.

As most of you aware, District Four cannot do e-learning right now because of the lack of internet access. We are aware this is one of the biggest challenges in our district.

This survey will give you the opportunity to express your concerns and share the good things that have been happening while students are learning from home. The link below will be available for about a week, and we would love for our families to complete and submit the survey.

https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/SAMD4

post_text:
UPDATE from WOODRUFF ELEMENTARY SCHOOL:

Governor McMaster announced Wednesday that students will not return to school for the remainder of this school year.

Educational Packet #2 will be taken up and Packet #3 will be distributed on MONDAY, APRIL 27, from 2:00pm – 6:00pm, and on TUESDAY, APRIL 28, from 7:30am – 12 noon.

All packets will be handled on the Tennis Courts side of the building. Packet #3 will include a letter with important information for parents. The packet will also include the student yearbook for any student who has previously purchased one.

PTA spring fundraiser items will be distributed on the Car Circle side of the building on the same dates/times. It will be necessary to drive through both circles if you need to pick up PTA fundraiser items.

It is very important that students and parents REMAIN IN VEHICLES while on campus- no exceptions!

WES is receiving reimbursements from companies that were used to book the field trips. Once reimbursement is made, WES will mail checks home to parents.

Though the art receptions have been canceled due to the pandemic, WHS art student winners and acceptances have been announced!

In the Young Women in Art at Converse, Anabel Evans placed 2nd in the sculpture category.

At the Focus on Youth at the Spartanburg Artists’ Guild, Ryleigh Henderson won 3rd overall.

In National Scholastics competition, Anabel Evans won a Silver Key.

At the Artfields Jr Competition, five works were selected to be part of the show. Congratulations to Anabel Evans, Wendy Garcia, Rosio Gonzalez, Grace Meaney, and Cori Rambow.

We’ve heard from so many folks who are appreciative of the meals that are being delivered! We are making a few adjustments beginning Monday, April 13.

In an effort to limit personal contact while continuing to feed our children, we are planning to prepare and deliver meals on Mondays, Wednesdays, and Fridays- two lunches /two breakfast on Mondays and Wednesdays, and one lunch / one breakfast on Fridays.

We are expecting the state to begin allowing weekend meals soon and once this happens, we will send two lunches and two breakfasts on Fridays as well.

We are also planning to operate the drive thru meal pickup at WHS on Mondays, Wednesdays, and Fridays.

We thank you for your understanding. Everyone stay safe and wash your hands, a lot!
#WolverineNationInThisTogether

UPDATE: WES Students

The next set of educational packets are being mailed out at this time. Some of you may have already received your packet. If you haven’t, they should arrive this week. If you do not receive a packet by Monday, April 13, please call WES (864-476-3123) so we can assist you.

Students may return their first packet from Tuesday, April 7 through Thursday, April 9 from 7:30am until 5:00 pm. Bins will be set up in the Car Circle side of the building. This is the side that faces the District Office. Please be sure the packet has your students first and last name on it. Please staple, paper clip or return the packet in the original envelope. Extra envelopes will be available beside the bins. Do not return text books.

Students nor parents will be allowed in the building.

Teachers will not handle or grade packets until April 20.

UPDATE: WMS 6th Graders

WMS will collect packets Tuesday, April 7-Thursday, April 9, from 7:30am-5:00pm. Materials will be collected in the Student Car Rider Area on the upper end of the campus. Please follow the usual flow of traffic by entering the drop off/pickup area through Theo Circle. Tables and bins will be under the awning. Grade level instructions and supplies you may need to turn in materials will be located at these stations.

These are the materials to turn in. Write YOUR NAME and your TEACHER’S NAME on all assignments that you turn in!

MATH
1. Tear out the assigned pages from your Volume 1 workbook and staple them together.
2. Tear out the assigned pages from your Volume 2 workbook and staple them together.

SCIENCE
Tear out and turn in the following:
1. Pages 500-501 (questions 1-14)
2. Pages 560-562 (questions 1-23)

SOCIAL STUDIES
1. Turn in the Coat of Arms project. This was a handout given to all students.

ELA
1. DO NOT turn in the Close Reader workbooks. The next set of assignments being mailed out are to be completed in the same Close Reader workbooks.

#WolverineNationInThisTogether on display in this email that Student Body President Aaron Groomes sent to the WHS Faculty and Staff!

Hey y'all! I hope y'all are staying safe during this crazy time! I just wanted to take a minute to thank each and every one of you for the hard work you have put in during this unprecedented situation. There is no easy way to prepare for a shut down this big this quick, but being the awesome teachers and staff that y'all are, y'all got it done, just like I knew you would. I'm so proud to serve with y'all and there's no where else I'd rather go to school. Again thank you for the hard work and keep it up. You guys are awesome!

Aaron Groomes
WHS Student Body President

The month of March is celebrated as Youth Art Month (YAM) across the nation. Each year the Spartanburg Fine Arts Department holds the Spartanburg County School Youth Art Month Exhibit. Only a few works are chosen from each Elementary, Middle, and High School from each district in Spartanburg County. This year’s works will be on display at the Chapman Cultural Center March 15 - April 30.

Congratulations to WMS students Lily Allison (Tokyo street scene); Bethany Stankus (drawing of hand and tree); Zoe Brown (drawing of bedroom); Cassidy Schiele (drawing of architecture); and Tatiyana Rodriquez (cat)!

post_text:
UPDATE:
All athletic activities are suspended through APRIL 5, based on the latest press release from from the South Carolina High School League (http://schsl.org/).

SCHSL: COVID-19/Coronavirus Update (3-16-20)
In accordance with the Executive Order by Governor McMaster, all South Carolina public schools are closed until the end of March. This includes SCHSL member schools with private schools strongly encouraged to follow suit. Regarding middle and high school athletics, the South Carolina High School League is suspending all Spring sport activities from March 16, 2020 through April 5, 2020. This suspension includes all contests, practices, workouts (conditioning and strength training), and/or open season skill development.

The COVID-19/Coronavirus is spreading across our state and nation with social distancing being critical to stop the spread. School athletics most certainly do not supersede the safety of our student-athletes, coaches, their families or fans.

post_text: District 4 Schools is deeply saddened to learn of the passing of one of our students, Jamaya Smith. Jamaya was a 9th grader at Woodruff High School. She had a kind spirit and uplifting attitude. We will all miss Jamaya’s bright smile and friendship. She will be deeply missed by both her teachers and classmates. We pray for her family and friends during this most difficult time. Our School Counselors will be available beginning Monday to help students in dealing with this tragic loss.

post_text:
WEATHER UPDATE:

District 4 will be operating on a 3-HOUR delay Friday, 2/21/20.

Buses will operate. No breakfast will be served at the schools.

District 4 is continuing to monitor the weather conditions in our area. Based on the information we have at this time from the National Weather Service, District Four schools will operate on a three hour delay. Our biggest concern is the freezing temperatures that are expected in Spartanburg County. We will continue to monitor the weather forecast as the evening progresses. Should the National Weather Service issue a black ice advisory overnight, we may make the decision to cancel school. Weather is sometimes difficult to predict but safety is always our top priority. Thank you for your patience and your understanding.

post_text:
Congratulations to Wolverine senior wrestlers Tony De La Garza and Noah Johns for being selected to compete in the North South All Star Tournament March 5-7, 2020, at North Myrtle Beach High School!
Tony De La Garza has a career record of 158-13. He is a 4-time Region Champion, 2018 Upperstate Champion, 2018 State Runner-Up, and is 2nd in All-Time in Career Wins and Career Pins at WHS. Noah Johns has a career record of 143-59, is the 2020 Region Champion, 2018 State Runner-Up, 2019 State Qualifier, and is 4th in All-Time in Career Wins and 3rd in All-Time in Career Pins at WHS.
text:

post_text: At 3:30am the National Weather Service issued a wind advisory that will remain in effect until 6pm. Based on this new information and an assessment of current road conditions, District Four will be CLOSED on February 7th. We understand this is not convenient for many parents but safety is always our top priority. The wind advisory warns of sustained winds of 15-25 mph and gusts of up to 45mph. We are concerned about the safe operation of our school buses as well as students and parents navigating around closed and damaged roads. Thank you for your patience and understanding as we navigate these weather-related conditions.

Lady Wolverine Zavia Jeter joins an elite group this evening as she scores her 1,000th point in tonight’s game against Emerald. The Lady Wolverines won the contest 64-42.

post_text: Teachers from Spartanburg District 4 and Spartanburg District 2 joined efforts to help North Central High School in Kershaw County after a tornado hit their school January 11, 2020. The SC Department of Education sent out a list of needs, and it didn’t take long for our Upstate teachers to get organized. Katie Darby from Spartanburg 2 and Ashley Bennett, teacher at Woodruff Middle, helped organize and gather donations from students and teachers. One student at Woodruff High school donated $100 to the cause! Mrs. Bennett and her husband Chris coordinate disaster relief ministry at their local church Church at The Mill and were able to utilize the church trailer to transport things after students helped load all the donations. What a team effort!

post_text: MUSE 134 and Stone Soup Storytelling Institute partnered with the Woodruff Elementary School Gifted Art Program to create an exhibit in December that showcased our young artists and historic Main Street Woodruff. When the local business owners viewed the exhibit, many owners asked to purchase the pieces! Owners of MUSE 134 Tom and Karen-Page Davies presented checks to students who had artwork purchased! Congratulations to Allison Morris, Alyssa Ballentine, Zeke Dickard, Allison Morris, Nathan McConnell, Lanah Nix, Maddie Nix and Ava Teague!

post_text: The Varsity Boys Basketball team was in the house supporting the JV team Monday evening as the JV took on Broome. Tuesday night, the Varsity Boys defeated Broome 61 to 49.
